<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Who knows. It's not how it went down. Anything beyond that is conjecture at this point.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
&quot;tough, we have peeps here and you do not, that's just the way it works.&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's just it. Having people there isn't the key. Having a raid capable force IS. Like the Venril Sathir attempt at a rant against MW from a group that spent their entire time spamming our rogues to unlock the door and let them in. Sure...you have a raid capable force, but you can't get into the room to kill the mob you want? How in god's name is that a &quot;raid capable force&quot;?<br>
<br>
And again, I repeat...How long do you tell that cleric who HAS the force to wait?<br>
<br>
I see the roll as a way to ensure the wait could continue without contention, to stall, essentially. Maybe I'm wrong. And I strongly disagreed with it, and probably always will, but I respected it anyway.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
Please explain it to me. If Sir Arther of Camelot led an army to slay a dragon, and came upon another army wanting to do the same thing for the glory of THEIR realm, would he have his knights trample them over so that they could slay the dragon first? Or would he ask the other army to join him in the battle to slay the beast, and that they would draw lots on who carried home his head?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If King Arthur and his army came across 6 people claiming they were going to conquer all of France, just as soon as they raised the army, should they have all gone home? Or should they have gone ahead and done what needed to be done?<br>
<br>
Seriously, I'm just looking for a number here. How long is a cleric with the force supposed to wait before it's no longer &quot;Greedy&quot; or &quot;rude&quot; to let their army at it? I'm genuinely curious.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
But you didn't race...there was nobody racing you. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You are quite mistaken in that. There were 2 other clerics who were at the Best of the Best desperately trying to get their porters and friends to leave. One of them was the one trying to offer me some 5k hammer or something if I let him &quot;have&quot; Rage and then, when I politely refused, exclaimed how very much it pissed him off to see a sub 55 cleric with epic.<br>
<br>
The fact that they didn't get there, and I did, however is fact.<br>
<br>
Sure, I lucked out. I'll be the first to admit it. Everyone was distracted by a large event. But most of the people that hate &quot;the race&quot; usually toss up Uberguilds as the reason they hate it, because they can't &quot;beat them in a race&quot;. Excuse me? Have you looked at the schedules these guys keep? You stand probably a 80% chance that if Rage pops, they are in the middle of clearing NToV or some other mobs.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
Since yours happened to be uncontended, it is somehow more valid than Lashanna's &quot;pathetic&quot; epic?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You probably wouldn't like my answer. The epic itself is nothing more than a nice mace with a right click effect that is very very handy. It's value is entirely in the owners hand. Just because other people are willing to settle for a roll, doesn't mean (and I stress again the opening line of this post &quot;If I had been required to roll, I would have walked&quot; not &quot;If I could control Brizzo and Lashanna with Psychic powers I would have made them walk&quot;) that I have to think that it's the best way. And I don't, for precisely the reasons I listed above.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
On the contrary, you will find that pretty much all of TRK and (from my experience) many of your guild disagree with you.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Disagrees with me on what? That it's ludicrious to be kicking your heels in the dirt waiting X* amount of time before it's &quot;ok&quot; for your force that was ready to go X* amount of time before without being deemed evil monsters just because they were prepared?<br>
<br>
*assuming anyone ever answers my above question about how long &quot;waiting&quot; before it's no longer greedy or rude.<br>
<br>
Was it amazingly nice and generous of all involved? Sure. Would I have looked down my nose at you for winning the race if you'd gone that route? No. Tactis, strategy, and efficient planning are something to be celebrated.  Does it change that to me the idea of the roll is completely abhorent? No.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
If I had totally ignored Brizzo's tell and his time camping Rage, and raced to the spawn and keeled him as MW got there, there would be a lot of hard feelings and lost respect on BOTH sides -- not just the losing side.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, I think you are wrong. Particularly of MW. We've never passed down the chance to add our forces when we didn't get there first. At least in the time I've been with them. And knowing the others, I doubt it's ever been different.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
I respected Brizzo's time and effort just as he respected Lashanna's. If that's not respect, I don't know what is.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And I respected my friend enough to not only to be there for him, but to take part in something I personally detest (the roll), because it was the *right thing to do*. Does this change that I think the roll is lame? No.<br>
<br>
Again, Adjani, CONCEPT. Not people.<br>
<br>
I *hate* the concept of the roll. Not you. Not your raid abilities. Not Lashanna for having her epic today. THE CONCEPT.<br>
<br>
Why is this so difficult to understand?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
I'd actually be really curious to read it. MW has changed a lot since the &quot;mass exodus&quot; to DAoC....I would be very interested to know MW's new stance on FFA, racing, etc., and if they support or tolerate the views you expressed put into action.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Mithril Web hasn't changed at all. The stance isn't new. <br>
<br>
Read the post that Keld put in the GL forum (unless it's scrolled since I had access to read). It's all right there.<br>
<br>
Some mobs are considered FFA, and always have been.<br>
<br>
(note: I'm not an officer, so if you want the official stance, you'll have to ask them. But I'm pretty confident that it's not changed that much from the listing I remember reading that Keld wrote up back when I was with ordo)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
I don't get your association of rolling and lists. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sorry, that's a Felis thing, since that's his pet cause.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
However when conflicts occur between raiding forces over epic mobs they are often rolled on, which is a totally different scenario altogether.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, I don't get it. It should be abundantly clear who has a force capable of taking down the mob. ie, &quot;Ok, you said you had a raid capable force, kill it.&quot; and then either watch them die, or back down, or kill it. But if they attempt to stall further, they aren't *ready* and someone else is, let them take that same test. &quot;Ok, kill it.&quot;<br>
<br>
There's really no way to fake being raid capable. You either are or you die.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
Felishanna posted about a specific incident, and you called the occurence in that incident lame and pathetic. You went on to describe how situations LIKE that are lame and pathetic. No, you never said that Lashanna, Adjani, and Brizzo are lame and pathetic but that makes it no less true that if A=B and B=C, then A=C.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Felis and I have done this dance many a time on many a post. Just because the discussion continued on this one did not mean that my issue with the concept behind rolling/lists immediately equate to &quot;you all suck for yesterday&quot;. I'm a pretty blunt individual. I don't really have any qualms telling someone exactly what I think of them. So trust me, if it had been about this specific incident, you WOULD know. Instead, yet again, as I do each time this topic rolls around, I talk about the concept and why it bugs me/disgusts me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
1. Isn't a primary quality of being a hero being honorable and respectful?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What's disrespectful about being prepared, ready, and raring to go invade France, while those 6 guys stand by the side of the road trying to recruit an army?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
2. How is offering someone a roll instead of just taking the spawn &quot;the easy way?&quot;<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Because, as I said, it promotes the idea (as I see it) that you can't get it any other way than if random luck assigns it to you. And I don't agree with that. At all.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <br>
Why don't we hear any stories of King Arthur of Camelot who trampled over his kind brother's army to get to the holy grail first? Because that's not the story of a hero either.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You have to have an army to be trampled. Otherwise you are just a spectator.<br>
<br>
