<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
First, you say this game is to make the average Joe turn into a hero. That is true, this game allows people to create a character who can accomplish some insane feats. Killing a Deity? Slaying some mighty Dragon? We can all do it, if we develop well enough.<br>
However, this at the same time provides a paradox. Since everyone eventually becomes a hero who slays Dragons (well, those that get high enough levels anyway) and such, they inadvertendly become the average Joe again.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But this isn't actually the case. What you are experiencing is that your relative surroundings are ....for lack of a better word for what I am trying to express....full of &quot;equals&quot;. I'm sure Hercules and Samson view themselves as old buds laughing about the time they pulled one too many skeletons and wiped out in Unrest, while the rest of the population views them as at the top and some unattainable place. We all did it. Saw some level 45 run by and thought to ourselves how godly that was and lamented the fact that we would probably never be that uber as the warrior in full crafted with two yaks.<br>
<br>
But every day a percentage of the people DO make it there. While the majority get to their 30s and start other characters, or just plain never break out of a certain level range. There are some ordos that it took over 2 years to get above level 20. <br>
<br>
But because we are surrounded by other people of our level range and general equipment, to us it seems as though we're still that goon that got killed 17 times trying to get his body away from the Nektulos Dark Elf guards (gods that was a miserable day <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ), and I'm sure even InsertHeroHere sat back listening to the bards sing of some great deed and suddenly went &quot;omfg! they are talking about me...I'm not a hero..I'm just some guy!&quot;<br>
<br>
You may remain an average joe in your own eyes, but heroes don't sing their own songs in these stories.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
So at times, even though we really like to be that hero, we must make a step to the side and leave room for that other hero.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In theory, yes, this sounds correct, but let me put it this way.<br>
<br>
Why should the cleric who is prepared and ready to go, be &quot;punished&quot; and the cleric who isn't &quot;Rewarded&quot;? What logic is that? To reduce all that skill, time, effort, and energy to something that rewards anyone regardless of time, effort, and energy. Why bother having your guild coming running at all. Just be in the zone and demand a roll, and then at their own leisure wander in to take him out because you won the /rand 0 100, while the cleric who had prepared for this day, had his friends on high alert, and was there in force, suddenly finds himself SOL, punished for being prepared.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
To roll means that you respect the fact that the others are entitled to their moment of glory just as much as you. And when only one can win that moment of glory, it takes a chance. Rolling - how unheroic ever - enables to make a clear determination. When no other discrimination is possible, it is the only way to see who gets it.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I disagree strongly with the entitlement. You are never entitled to glory. You earn it. Again, why is the one who is prepared punished, and the one who isn't rewarded? There is no entitlement as I see it. There is simply who wanted it badly enough to be prepared.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Even so, if you do roll and loose the roll, thereby more or less &quot;officialy&quot; settling who gets his moment of glory, you also win. You win the respect from that other. One day, your turn will come. It may not be today, it may not be tomorrow, but maybe the day after that? Or next week?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Let me give you a prime example.<br>
<br>
When we did another guild cleric's epic, there were 3 clerics in the lair. All three sent out the call. By the time any other guild arrived, and not even raid capable, just arrived, we were almost complete buffing and getting into position for the kill.<br>
<br>
They respected we were there first, and offered to help, recognizing that someone else had been better prepared that time. Had MW ported in and found Adjani's raid capable force, you better believe we would have asked &quot;Need a few more swords and a bit of healing?&quot; There was a race once that I think it was you (?) had posted to the raves forum about 3 guilds racing to Rage, and when they got there, it was clear who was there in force first, and the other two added their numbers.<br>
<br>
There is no disrepect in the race. But I see tons of disrespect in the roll punishing those who are ready and rewarding those who want to stall the process, even if it means losing their chance because they have decided that they know they won't win any other way. (again this is not about a specific incident in any of this, I am speaking in general terms <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  before adjani bites my head off thinking I am talking about her raid :P)<br>
